  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The UAM IT Architecture &lt;em>discipline&lt;/em> has very wide applicability; the enterprise as a whole, or a project&#xD;
    architecture. The “system”&amp;nbsp;in any enteprise context includes software, hardware, processes,&amp;nbsp;and people.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_UAM__discipline&quot; name=&quot;XE_UAM__discipline&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The purposes of the UAM IT Architecture discipline are:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To transform the requirements into a design of the &lt;em>to-be&lt;/em> system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To document an existing &lt;em>as-is&lt;/em> system;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To evolve a robust IT architecture for the enterprise, business line, and other contexts, addressing all the&#xD;
        relevant views and viewpoints;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To clearly specify the interfaces between the defined system components, entities, and people;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        To create all the prerequisite artifacts needed for system development: various architectural views at multiple&#xD;
        levels.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The processes and tasks needed to define UAM IT architectures are included within this discipline definition.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
